    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Posterior urethral valves are the most common cause of lower urinary tract obstruction in male neonates, leading to a spectrum of urological and renal complications. Early detection, often antenatally, is paramount for preserving renal function and guiding timely intervention.\\n\\n| Diagnostic Modality | Key Finding for PUV | Timing/Purpose | Clinical Implication |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Antenatal Ultrasound | Keyhole sign (dilated posterior urethra), thickened bladder, hydronephrosis, oligohydramnios | Prenatal screening/initial suspicion | Prompts postnatal evaluation, potential fetal intervention |\\n| MCUG (VCUG) | Dilated posterior urethra, abrupt caliber change, VUR, bladder changes | Gold standard for definitive postnatal diagnosis | Confirms diagnosis, guides surgical planning (valve ablation) |\\n",
