    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Pyloromyotomy (Ramstedt's procedure) involves incising the hypertrophied circular muscle fibers of the pylorus longitudinally, extending from the prepyloric vein of Mayo proximally to the duodenal mucosa distally, while carefully preserving the underlying submucosa and mucosa. The goal is to relieve the obstruction by allowing the mucosa to bulge through the incised muscle, effectively widening the pyloric channel. Incomplete myotomy occurs when the muscle fibers are not fully divided, or the incision does not extend adequately, leading to persistent obstruction.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** Postoperative emesis is common after pyloromyotomy due to gastric edema, dysmotility, or feeding intolerance. However, persistent, projectile, or increasing emesis beyond the initial 24-48 hours, particularly on the third postoperative day, mandates investigation for an incomplete myotomy. A barium meal (upper GI series) is the definitive diagnostic modality, revealing delayed gastric emptying, a persistent 'string sign,' or a 'double-track sign' if the muscle is still significantly obstructing. This diagnostic step is crucial to differentiate benign postoperative emesis from a surgical complication requiring re-intervention.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Infantile Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis is a common cause of gastric outlet obstruction in neonates, characterized by hypertrophy of the pyloric muscle. Early diagnosis and correction of electrolyte imbalances are paramount before surgical pyloromyotomy. Postoperative care focuses on gradual feeding advancement and vigilance for complications like incomplete myotomy.\\n\\n| Clinical Presentation | Diagnostic Ultrasound Criteria | Preoperative Management | Postoperative Complications |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Projectile non-bilious vomiting, 'olive' mass, hungry after feeds | Muscle thickness >3-4mm, Length >14-17mm, Diameter >10-14mm | IV fluids (D5 0.45% NS with 20 mEq/L KCl), correct hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis | Incomplete myotomy, mucosal perforation, wound infection, persistent emesis |\\n| Typically 2-8 weeks old, male predominance, first-born | Target sign (transverse), Antral nipple sign (longitudinal) | NPO, NG tube for decompression (if severe distension), monitor electrolytes | Gastric dysmotility, feeding intolerance, jaundice (rare) |\\n",
    "P_plan_for_improvement": "**The Board Pearl:** *If a neonate presents with projectile non-bilious vomiting and an 'olive-shaped' mass, *always* correct hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis *before* surgical pyloromyotomy, as operating on an unresuscitated infant significantly increases anesthetic and surgical risk.*"
