    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Alkaline button batteries, particularly lithium coin cells, pose a severe risk of liquefaction necrosis due to current generation and hydroxide ion release. While esophageal impaction is most critical, intestinal passage still carries perforation risk, especially if lodged or if the battery casing is compromised. Beyond the stomach, endoscopic retrieval becomes challenging or impossible, making surgical intervention the definitive method for removal and inspection of the bowel.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** For an alkaline battery located in the small intestine, endoscopic retrieval is generally not feasible or safe due to the length and tortuosity of the bowel, and the inability to adequately protect the mucosa during extraction. Given the high risk of mucosal injury, perforation, and stricture formation from alkaline batteries, surgical exploration with enterotomy and direct removal is indicated. The asymptomatic status is misleading; damage can occur rapidly and silently, making prophylactic removal paramount.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Alkaline battery ingestion in children is a surgical emergency due to the rapid and severe corrosive injury potential. Location dictates management: esophageal impaction requires immediate endoscopic removal, while batteries beyond the stomach but still in the GI tract require careful monitoring or surgical removal depending on location, type, and symptoms. Intestinal location often necessitates surgical intervention due to the limitations of endoscopy and the ongoing risk of damage.\\n\\n| Battery Location | Risk/Urgency | Management Strategy | Key Consideration |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Esophagus | High (perforation, fistula) | Immediate endoscopic removal | Time-sensitive; liquefaction necrosis |\\n| Stomach (Alkaline) | High (if lodged or large) | Endoscopic removal if accessible; otherwise surgical | Observe if small, non-alkaline, and passing |\\n| Intestine (Alkaline) | High (perforation, stricture) | Surgical removal (laparotomy/enterotomy) | Endoscopy difficult/impossible; ongoing corrosive injury |\\n| Intestine (Non-alkaline, small) | Low-Moderate | Observe, stool checks, repeat X-ray | Most pass spontaneously; monitor for symptoms |\\n",
    "P_plan_for_improvement": "**The Board Pearl:** *If an alkaline battery is beyond endoscopic reach in the intestine, *even if asymptomatic*, surgical removal is the safest course to prevent silent, progressive corrosive injury and perforation.*"
