    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Superior vena cava (SVC) syndrome, particularly in pediatric oncology patients with mediastinal masses (e.g., lymphoma), frequently involves significant tracheal compression. The loss of airway tone during anesthetic induction, especially with muscle relaxants, can lead to complete tracheal collapse and catastrophic airway obstruction. The patient's orthopnea, tachypnea, and tachycardia are clear indicators of impending respiratory failure due to this compression.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** The immediate, life-saving priority is to establish and maintain a patent airway. While the option mentions 'rapid-sequence induction,' the critical takeaway is the *immediate securement of the airway*. In such cases, a controlled, often inhalational, induction with spontaneous ventilation maintained is generally preferred to preserve airway tone. Awake fiberoptic intubation or even readiness for rigid bronchoscopy or ECMO may be necessary. Delaying airway management for diagnostic imaging, biopsy, or medical therapy is contraindicated when acute airway compromise is present.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Superior vena cava (SVC) syndrome is a medical emergency caused by obstruction of the SVC, leading to impaired venous drainage from the head, neck, and upper extremities. In children, it is most commonly associated with mediastinal masses (e.g., lymphoma, neuroblastoma). Airway compromise due to tracheal compression is a life-threatening complication requiring immediate, expert intervention.\\n\\n| Severity of SVC Syndrome | Key Clinical Finding | Immediate Management Priority | Anesthetic Consideration |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Mild/Moderate | Facial/neck edema, dilated collateral veins, cough | Imaging (CT/MRI) & Biopsy planning | Careful anesthetic planning, consider awake intubation |\\n| Severe/Impending Airway | Dyspnea, stridor, orthopnea, altered mental status, cyanosis | Airway stabilization (intubation, ECMO readiness) | Avoid muscle relaxants, maintain spontaneous ventilation, inhalational induction |\\n",
