    "correct": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Wilms tumor, or nephroblastoma, is the most common pediatric renal malignancy. Its biological behavior is characterized by a pseudocapsule that, when intact, confines the tumor. Rupture of this capsule, whether spontaneous, during biopsy, or intraoperatively, releases viable tumor cells into the peritoneal cavity or retroperitoneum. This local dissemination fundamentally alters the disease burden from a localized process to one with regional spread, necessitating a change in treatment intensity. The Children's Oncology Group (COG) staging system (formerly NWTSG) explicitly incorporates tumor rupture as a criterion for upstaging.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** For an operating surgeon, preventing tumor rupture is paramount. This requires meticulous, en bloc resection of the kidney and tumor within Gerota's fascia, minimizing manipulation. If rupture occurs, it immediately shifts the treatment paradigm, mandating a more aggressive chemotherapy regimen and often abdominal radiation, even if the tumor was otherwise localized. The surgeon's intraoperative documentation of rupture is critical for the oncologist's post-operative planning.",
