    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Wilms tumor, or nephroblastoma, is the most common pediatric renal malignancy. Its biological behavior is characterized by a pseudocapsule that, when intact, confines the tumor. Rupture of this capsule, whether spontaneous, during biopsy, or intraoperatively, releases viable tumor cells into the peritoneal cavity or retroperitoneum. This local dissemination fundamentally alters the disease burden from a localized process to one with regional spread, necessitating a change in treatment intensity. The Children's Oncology Group (COG) staging system (formerly NWTSG) explicitly incorporates tumor rupture as a criterion for upstaging.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** For an operating surgeon, preventing tumor rupture is paramount. This requires meticulous, en bloc resection of the kidney and tumor within Gerota's fascia, minimizing manipulation. If rupture occurs, it immediately shifts the treatment paradigm, mandating a more aggressive chemotherapy regimen and often abdominal radiation, even if the tumor was otherwise localized. The surgeon's intraoperative documentation of rupture is critical for the oncologist's post-operative planning.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Wilms tumor staging is primarily surgical, with intraoperative findings dictating the stage and subsequent adjuvant therapy. Tumor rupture, whether spontaneous or iatrogenic, is a critical event that upstages the disease, significantly intensifying the required chemotherapy and often necessitating radiation therapy, impacting prognosis.\\n\\n| COG Stage | Key Surgical/Pathologic Finding | Adjuvant Therapy Implications | Prognostic Impact |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Stage I | Tumor completely resected, confined to kidney | Chemotherapy (low-risk regimens) | Excellent (90-95% survival) |\\n| Stage II | Tumor extends beyond kidney but completely resected (e.g., renal sinus invasion, vessel invasion beyond kidney) | More intensive chemotherapy | Very good (85-90% survival) |\\n| Stage III | Residual non-hematogenous tumor (e.g., tumor rupture with spillage, positive margins, lymph node involvement, unresectable tumor) | Intensive chemotherapy + Abdominal Radiation | Good (75-85% survival) |\\n| Stage IV | Hematogenous metastases (e.g., lung, liver, bone, brain) | Intensive chemotherapy + Radiation to metastatic sites | Fair (60-70% survival) |\\n| Stage V | Bilateral renal involvement at diagnosis | Staged individually for each kidney, intensive chemotherapy | Variable, often worse than unilateral |\\n",
