    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Intussusception involves the telescoping of a proximal bowel segment (intussusceptum) into a distal segment (intussuscipiens), most commonly the ileum into the colon at the ileocecal valve. This mechanical obstruction leads to venous and lymphatic congestion, bowel wall edema, hemorrhage, and ultimately arterial compromise, ischemia, and necrosis. The 'currant jelly' stool results from sloughed mucosa and blood.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** The clinical presentation mandates immediate diagnostic imaging, typically ultrasound, which reveals the characteristic 'target sign' or 'pseudokidney sign'. Initial management involves non-operative hydrostatic or pneumatic reduction (air enema) under fluoroscopic or ultrasound guidance, provided there are no signs of peritonitis, perforation, or prolonged obstruction. Surgical intervention is reserved for failed non-operative reduction, signs of peritonitis, or bowel perforation.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Intussusception is the most common cause of intestinal obstruction in infants aged 3 months to 3 years. It is a surgical emergency requiring prompt diagnosis and management to prevent bowel ischemia, perforation, and sepsis. While most cases are idiopathic, pathological lead points (e.g., Meckel's diverticulum, polyp, lymphoma) should be considered, especially in older children or recurrent cases.\\n\\n| Clinical Feature | Diagnostic Imaging | Management (First-line) | Complications |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Sudden, colicky pain, vomiting, currant jelly stool, palpable mass | Abdominal Ultrasound: Target/Pseudokidney sign | Air/Hydrostatic Enema Reduction | Bowel ischemia, perforation, peritonitis |\\n| Age 3 months - 3 years (peak 5-9 months) | CT (if ultrasound equivocal or for lead point) | Surgical Reduction/Resection (if enema fails or contraindications) | Recurrence (5-10%) |\\n",
