    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Omphalocele is a midline abdominal wall defect occurring at the umbilical ring, characterized by herniation of abdominal viscera (often liver and bowel) encased within a sac composed of amnion, Wharton's jelly, and peritoneum. This is distinct from gastroschisis, which is a paraumbilical defect, typically to the right of the umbilical cord, where bowel is exposed and lacks a covering sac.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** Precise prenatal diagnosis and postnatal differentiation are critical for surgical planning. Omphaloceles are frequently associated with other major congenital anomalies (e.g., cardiac, chromosomal, Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome), necessitating a comprehensive systemic workup. Gastroschisis, while requiring urgent surgical closure, is less commonly associated with other major systemic anomalies, though intestinal complications like atresia or malrotation are common.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Congenital abdominal wall defects and omphalomesenteric duct anomalies represent distinct embryological failures requiring precise diagnostic differentiation for appropriate management. Understanding their embryological origins dictates clinical presentation and associated anomalies.\\n\\n| Anomaly | Embryological Origin | Key Feature | Associated Anomalies |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Omphalocele | Failure of midgut return/closure of umbilical ring | Midline defect, sac-covered viscera | Cardiac, chromosomal, Beckwith-Wiedemann |\\n| Gastroschisis | Paraumbilical defect, possibly vascular insult | Paraumbilical defect, exposed viscera | Intestinal atresia, malrotation (less systemic) |\\n| Meckel's Diverticulum | Incomplete obliteration of vitelline duct (intestinal end) | True diverticulum, ectopic tissue (2% rule) | None typically, but can cause bleeding/obstruction |\\n| Umbilical Polyp | Persistent omphalomesenteric duct mucosa | Red, moist umbilical lesion | None typically |\\n",
    "P_plan_for_improvement": "**The Board Pearl:** *If the abdominal wall defect is *at* the umbilicus and *covered*, think Omphalocele (and associated anomalies); if *lateral* to the umbilicus and *uncovered*, think Gastroschisis (and isolated bowel issues).*"
