    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Biliary atresia is a critical cause of neonatal cholestasis, requiring prompt diagnosis and surgical intervention (Kasai portoenterostomy) to prevent irreversible liver damage. Despite successful Kasai, many patients will eventually require liver transplantation due to progressive liver disease. Early diagnosis and referral are paramount.\\n\\n| Clinical Feature/Finding | Diagnostic Modality/Sign | Initial Surgical Management | Long-term Outcome/Complication |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Neonatal cholestasis (jaundice >2 weeks, acholic stools, dark urine) | Triangular Cord Sign (ultrasound), Absent/Small Gallbladder | Kasai Portoenterostomy (HPE) | Progressive cirrhosis, portal hypertension, cholangitis, liver failure |\\n| Elevated direct bilirubin, GGT, ALP | Liver biopsy (bile duct proliferation, fibrosis, cholestasis) | Nutritional support (fat-soluble vitamins, MCTs) | Liver transplantation (frequent endpoint post-Kasai) |\\n",
