    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Congenital abdominal wall defects, primarily gastroschisis and omphalocele, represent distinct embryological failures with differing clinical presentations, associated anomalies, and management strategies. Accurate prenatal diagnosis and differentiation are crucial for appropriate counseling and postnatal care. While both involve herniation of abdominal contents, the presence of a covering sac and the association with other anomalies are key discriminators.\\n\\n| Feature | Gastroschisis | Omphalocele | Clinical Pivot |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Covering Membrane | Absent (bowel exposed) | Present (peritoneum/amnion) | Immediate visual differentiator in OR/imaging |\\n| Umbilical Cord | Intact, usually to the left of defect | Inserts onto the sac | Location relative to defect |\\n| Associated Anomalies | Rare (isolated defect) | Frequent (cardiac, GU, chromosomal, GI) | Dictates extent of prenatal/postnatal workup |\\n| Bowel Appearance | Matted, edematous, inflamed | Normal, protected by sac | Impacts feasibility of primary closure |\\n| Etiology | Vascular insult/lateral fold defect | Failure of midgut return | Embryological basis for distinct presentations |\\n| Management | Silo for staged reduction common | Primary closure or staged sac coverage | Influences surgical approach and timing |\\n",
