    "B": "Mild emesis can occur post-pyloromyotomy due to gastric dysmotility or edema, especially in the first 24-48 hours. Persistent, significant emesis beyond 5-7 days, or immediate severe emesis, raises suspicion for incomplete myotomy. Barium studies are rarely needed; repeat ultrasound or clinical observation is usually sufficient. For this option to be correct, the emesis would need to be persistent and severe beyond 5-7 days, and the diagnostic approach would typically start with ultrasound.",
