    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Chronic vomiting in IHPS leads to significant loss of gastric acid (HCl) and potassium, resulting in hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis. The body attempts to compensate by retaining bicarbonate and excreting potassium in the urine, exacerbating hypokalemia. This fluid and electrolyte imbalance, if uncorrected, significantly increases anesthetic and surgical risks, particularly respiratory depression and cardiac arrhythmias. Preoperative correction of dehydration and electrolyte abnormalities is non-negotiable for safe pyloromyotomy.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** Before any surgical intervention for IHPS, the patient's metabolic alkalosis, hypochloremia, and hypokalemia must be corrected. This involves intravenous fluid resuscitation with normal saline (0.9% NaCl) with added potassium chloride (KCl). Adequate resuscitation is indicated by normalization of serum chloride (>100 mEq/L), potassium (4.5-6.5 mEq/L), and a decrease in serum bicarbonate/CO2 (<30 mEq/L). Surgery is deferred until these parameters are within acceptable limits, typically 24-48 hours of aggressive fluid and electrolyte management.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Infantile Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis is a common cause of gastric outlet obstruction in infants, characterized by hypertrophy of the pyloric muscle. It presents with progressive, projectile non-bilious vomiting, often leading to dehydration, electrolyte imbalances (hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis), and failure to thrive. Diagnosis is primarily clinical, confirmed by abdominal ultrasound. Management is surgical (pyloromyotomy) but requires meticulous preoperative correction of fluid and electrolyte deficits.\\n\\n| Clinical Presentation | Diagnostic Criteria (US) | Preoperative Management | Surgical Principle |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Projectile non-bilious vomiting, 'olive' mass, hungry after feeds | Pyloric muscle thickness \u22653-4mm, Pyloric channel length \u226514-17mm | Correct dehydration, hypochloremia, hypokalemia, metabolic alkalosis | Ramstedt pyloromyotomy (longitudinal incision through serosa and muscle, sparing mucosa) |\\n| Dehydration, weight loss, hypochloremic hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis | Target sign on transverse view, elongated pyloric canal | IV fluids (0.9% NaCl + KCl), monitor electrolytes/blood gas | Ensure complete myotomy, avoid mucosal perforation |\\n",
