    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Intestinal malrotation is a congenital anomaly of gut development that can lead to life-threatening midgut volvulus. Ladd's procedure is the definitive surgical correction, aiming to prevent volvulus by widening the mesenteric base and repositioning the bowel.\\n\\n| Clinical Presentation | Key Diagnostic Imaging | Immediate Surgical Intervention | Ladd's Procedure Steps |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Bilious emesis (neonate) | Upper GI series: Ligament of Treitz to right of midline, corkscrew duodenum | Emergent laparotomy for detorsion | Counter-clockwise detorsion, Ladd's band division, mesenteric broadening, appendectomy, bowel repositioning (small bowel right, colon left, cecum LLQ) |\\n| Chronic abdominal pain/vomiting (older child) | Upper GI series, CT abdomen: abnormal vessel relationship (SMA/SMV inversion) | Elective or urgent laparotomy | Counter-clockwise detorsion, Ladd's band division, mesenteric broadening, appendectomy, bowel repositioning (small bowel right, colon left, cecum LLQ) |\\n",
