    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Hirschsprung's disease is a congenital absence of enteric ganglion cells, causing functional obstruction. Its most life-threatening complication is Hirschsprung's enterocolitis (HEC), characterized by inflammation, dilation, and potential perforation of the proximal, normally innervated colon. Early diagnosis and surgical management are critical to prevent morbidity and mortality.\\n\\n| Disease Type | Pathophysiology | Clinical Presentation of HEC | Surgical Management of Perforation |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Short-segment HD | Aganglionosis limited to rectosigmoid | Abdominal distension, bilious emesis, explosive stools post-DRE, fever, lethargy, bloody diarrhea | Resuscitation, proximal diverting ostomy (ileostomy/colostomy), resection of perforated segment |\\n| Long-segment HD / Total Colonic Aganglionosis | Aganglionosis extending beyond rectosigmoid, potentially entire colon | Severe abdominal distension, intractable constipation, failure to thrive, signs of sepsis, peritonitis | Resuscitation, proximal diverting ileostomy (often), resection of perforated segment |\\n",
    "P_plan_for_improvement": "**The Board Pearl:** *If a neonate with Hirschsprung's disease presents with acute abdominal distension, signs of sepsis, and peritonitis, *always* suspect Hirschsprung's enterocolitis with perforation, and *always* look to the cecum or proximal colon as the most likely site of rupture due to maximal distension and wall tension.*"
