    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Necrotizing enterocolitis is an acute inflammatory disease of the bowel, primarily affecting premature infants, characterized by intestinal necrosis, often leading to perforation and significant morbidity/mortality. Its pathogenesis is multifactorial, involving gut immaturity, dysbiosis, and ischemic injury.\\n\\n| Bell's Stage | Clinical/Radiographic Finding | Management | Prognostic Factor |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Stage I (Suspect) | Abdominal distension, feeding intolerance, occult blood, mild lethargy | NPO, IV fluids, antibiotics, serial exams/X-rays | Prematurity, low birth weight |\\n| Stage II (Definite) | Pneumatosis intestinalis, portal venous gas, abdominal tenderness | NPO, IV fluids, broad-spectrum antibiotics, gastric decompression | Extent of bowel involvement |\\n| Stage III (Advanced) | Perforation (pneumoperitoneum), fixed dilated loops, severe acidosis, shock | Resuscitation, emergent laparotomy (resection, ostomy) | Perforation, diffuse necrosis, need for multiple resections |\\n",
