    "takeaway": "An impalpable testis in a child older than 6 months mandates surgical exploration due to the high likelihood of finding a gonad and the benefits of early intervention.",
    "visualization": "During inguinal exploration, the surgeon visualizes the external oblique aponeurosis, opens the inguinal canal, and identifies the spermatic cord structures. The undescended testis is typically found within the canal, often adherent to the internal ring or within the preperitoneal space, requiring careful dissection to mobilize it for scrotal placement."
