    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Thyroglossal duct cysts are the most common congenital midline neck masses, arising from incomplete obliteration of the thyroglossal duct. They are typically painless, mobile, and cystic, often presenting in childhood. The definitive treatment is surgical excision via the Sistrunk procedure to prevent recurrence and potential complications.\\n\\n| Location/Type | Key Clinical Feature | Diagnostic Confirmation | Definitive Management |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Midline, moves with tongue protrusion/deglutition, often infrahyoid | Ultrasound (cystic, relation to hyoid) | Sistrunk Procedure (cyst + central hyoid + tract to foramen cecum) |\\n| Dermoid Cyst | Midline, often suprahyoid, doughy/firm, does NOT move with tongue/deglutition | Ultrasound/MRI (cystic/solid components, no connection to hyoid/thyroid) | Simple Excision |\\n| Ectopic Thyroid | Midline, firm, can be anywhere along duct path, may be sole thyroid tissue | Thyroid Scan (I-123/Tc-99m), Ultrasound | Observation if asymptomatic, careful consideration if sole thyroid tissue (hormone replacement if excised) |\\n",
