    "correct": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Testicular descent is a complex embryological process involving hormonal, mechanical, and genetic factors. Cryptorchidism, or failure of descent, most commonly results in the testis arresting along its normal path, typically within the inguinal canal (approximately 80-90% of cases) or in the superficial inguinal pouch, an ectopic but still inguinal location. True intra-abdominal testes are less frequent, and agenesis is rare. An impalpable testis indicates it is not in the scrotum, but does not definitively mean it is intra-abdominal; it is frequently high in the inguinal canal or just outside the external ring.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** For an impalpable testis, the initial surgical approach is typically an inguinal exploration. This allows for identification of the testis or its remnants, and if found, mobilization and orchidopexy into the scrotum. The high probability of finding the testis in the inguinal region justifies this as the first-line surgical strategy, minimizing the need for more invasive laparoscopic exploration unless the inguinal exploration is negative.",
