    "H_highlight_excellence": "**Surgical Mechanism:** Prolonged vomiting in pyloric stenosis results in the loss of gastric acid (HCl) and potassium. The initial loss of hydrogen ions leads to metabolic alkalosis. As the body attempts to compensate, bicarbonate is retained, and potassium is excreted in the urine in exchange for sodium and hydrogen ions (paradoxical aciduria). This renal compensation, coupled with direct gastric potassium loss, exacerbates hypokalemia. Intracellular potassium shifts out to buffer the alkalosis, further depleting serum levels. The hypochloremia also impairs renal bicarbonate excretion, perpetuating the alkalosis.\\n\\n**Clinical Execution:** For an operating surgeon, correcting hypokalemia and metabolic alkalosis is paramount before pyloromyotomy. Uncorrected electrolyte imbalances, particularly severe hypokalemia, significantly increase the risk of cardiac arrhythmias and respiratory depression during anesthesia. Preoperative fluid resuscitation with normal saline and potassium supplementation is crucial to restore electrolyte balance and optimize surgical outcomes.",
    "A_address_the_gaps": "",
    "R_review_learning_points": "**Conceptual Overview:** Pyloric stenosis is a common cause of non-bilious projectile vomiting in infants, leading to a characteristic metabolic derangement of hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis. Preoperative correction of these electrolyte abnormalities is critical for safe surgical intervention.\\n\\n| Electrolyte Imbalance | Mechanism in Pyloric Stenosis | Clinical Consequence | Preoperative Management |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| Hypokalemia | Gastric loss, renal excretion (paradoxical aciduria), intracellular shift | Cardiac arrhythmias, muscle weakness, ileus | IV potassium chloride supplementation |\\n| Hypochloremia | Gastric HCl loss, renal bicarbonate retention | Perpetuates metabolic alkalosis | IV normal saline (chloride replacement) |\\n| Metabolic Alkalosis | Loss of H+ ions, renal bicarbonate retention | Respiratory depression, seizures, cardiac irritability | Fluid resuscitation, electrolyte correction |\\n",
    "P_plan_for_improvement": "**The Board Pearl:** *If an infant presents with projectile non-bilious vomiting and a palpable 'olive' mass, *always* anticipate hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis and correct electrolytes *before* surgery.*"
